Hi!

It is a common pattern in XML to have a container element in the plural form for repeating element (lists, etc) like this :
```xml
<root>
   <documents>
	<document>
		<texte>word1</texte>
	</document>
	<document>
		<texte>word2</texte>
	</document>
   </documents>
</root>
```

I noticed that then xmltodict output a dictionary with  one child as key. In the end we have  twice the "same" conceptual node. like this  : 

```json
{
    "documents": {
        "document": [
            {
                "texte": "word1"
            },
	    {
		"texte": "word2"
	    }
         ]
    }
}
```
I am aware that there could be two different elements repeated as children of the container but when it is not the case  I would like to have an option to output something like this 

```json
{
     "document": [
         {
              "texte": "word1"
         },
         {
	      "texte": "word2"
	 }
     ]
}
```

This option would produce such an output only when there is only one repeated element name children of the container element.

What is your opinion on this ? would you accept a pull request in that direction (with an option that default to the current behavior of course) ? Would it be easy for you to point us to the part of the code managing repetition (array creation) ?

Thanks a lot for your time.

from flask import Flask
from flask_jwt import JWT, jwt_required, current_identity
from werkzeug.security import safe_str_cmp

class User(object):
    def __init__(self, id, username, password):
        self.id = id
        self.username = username
        self.password = password

    def __str__(self):
        return "User(id='%s')" % self.id

users = [ User(1,'user1','abcxyz'),User(2,'user2','abcxyz'),]

username_table = {u.username: u for u in users}
userid_table = {u.id: u for u in users}

def authenticate(username, password):
    user = username_table.get(username, None)
    if user and safe_str_cmp(user.password.encode('utf-8'), password.encode('utf-8')):
        return user

def identity(payload):
    user_id = payload['identity']
    return userid_table.get(user_id, None)

app = Flask(__name__)

app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = 'super-secret'

jwt = JWT(app, authenticate, identity)

@app.route('/protected')
@jwt_required()
def protected():
    return '%s' % current_identity

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)


